	('36821329-5159-4e83-9cf5-baed78f3a385', '78b1e1bd-03ca-4f20-a28d-28552895a514', 'ESA Graduate Trainee in Evaluation and Data Analytics', 'f2601046-ce81-48ef-8e14-db89efcd7aa6', 'Paris, FR', 'Location ESA Headquarters, Paris, France Our team and mission ESAâ€™s Evaluation Office is part of the Internal Audit and Evaluation team, within the Director Generalâ€™s Services. We are a cross-functional team, composed of highly skilled professionals. The team is in charge of the planning and implementing the continual improvement actions of the Agencyâ€™s management practices. We leverage internal and external competences in: evaluation, advanced data analytics, process assessment and design, lean management and digital transformation to facilitate the changes required for the Agency to maintain and improve its competitive advantage. The Evaluation Team is providing consultancy service to ESA management aimed at: Improving the efficiency and effectiveness of the Agencyâ€™s activities. Assessing and advising on the business models of the Agency and of its directorates, identifying opportunities for optimisation Supporting the transformation of the Agency by conducting independent analyses and benchmarks, Advising process owners on business process optimisation and supporting their implementation, as required Assessing and advising on the evolution of corporate databases and fostering the implementation of data mining techniques, AI and automation for the optimisation of business processes; providing benchmark services to directorates Building the Digital Twin ESA, which is a digital replica of the whole management system of the Agency Field(s) of activity/research for the traineeship The Evaluation Office is a unique environment to start the professional career of an ESA Graduate Trainee, offering the opportunity to actively work on the processes that govern an international organisation. As an EGT, you will perform the following activities as required by the evaluation projects, including: Performing advanced data analytics from internal and external data sources, as well as from unstructured data (e.g. text, written reports) to identify areas for evaluation in ESA, and to help establishing performance measurements, internal or external benchmarks. Creating visualisations using Power BI to create impactful presentations Re-engineering of management processes at Agency and Directorate level, focusing on their streamlining and digitalisation Drafting clear reports on evaluation findings and recommendations Technical competencies Knowledge of relevant technical/functional domainsRelevant experience gained during internships, project work and/or extracurricular or other activitiesGeneral knowledge of the space sector and relevant activitiesKnowledge of ESA and its programmes/projectsBehavioural competencies Result Orientation Operational Efficiency Fostering Cooperation Relationship Management Continuous Improvement Forward Thinking For more information, please refer to ESA Core Behavioural Competencies guidebook Education You should have just completed, or be in the final year of your masterâ€™s degree in data analytics, data science, mathematics, statistics, economics, computer science or business Additional requirements You should have good interpersonal and communication skills and should be able to work in a multicultural environment, both independently and as part of a team. Previous experience of working in international teams can be considered an asset. Your motivation, overall professional perspective and career goals will also be explored during the later stages of the selection process. It is also expected that the selected EGT will possess at least one of the following skills: Programming skills (e.g. Python, SQL, R) Data, AI or Prompt Engineering skills Data Warehousing skills Knowledge of MS Azure and MS Power (e.g. Power BI, Power Apps) Diversity, Equity and Inclusiveness ESA is an equal opportunity employer, committed to achieving diversity within the workforce and creating an inclusive working environment. We therefore welcome applications from all qualified candidates irrespective of gender, sexual orientation, ethnicity, beliefs, age, disability or other characteristics. Applications from women are encouraged. At the Agency we value diversity, and we welcome people with disabilities. Whenever possible, we seek to accommodate individuals with disabilities by providing the necessary support at the workplace. The Human Resources Department can also provide assistance during the recruitment process. If you would like to discuss this further, please contact us via email at contact.human.resources@esa.int. Important Information and Disclaimer During the recruitment process, the Agency may request applicants to undergo selection tests. Additionally, successful candidates will need to undergo basic screening before appointment, which will be conducted by an external background screening service, in compliance with the European Space Agency''s security procedures. The information published on ESAâ€™s careers website regarding working conditions is correct at the time of publication. It is not intended to be exhaustive and may not address all questions you would have. Nationality and Languages Please note that applications can only be considered from nationals of one of the following States: Austria, Belgium, Czechia, Denmark, Estonia, Finland, France, Germany, Greece, Hungary, Ireland, Italy, Luxembourg, the Netherlands, Norway, Poland, Portugal, Romania, Slovenia, Spain, Sweden, Switzerland, and the United Kingdom. Nationals from Latvia, Lithuania and Slovakia as Associate Member States, or Canada as a Cooperating State, can apply as well as those from Bulgaria, Croatia, Cyprus and Malta as European Cooperating States (ECS). According to the ESA Convention, the recruitment of staff must take into account an adequate distribution of posts among nationals of the ESA Member States*. When short-listing for an interview, priority will be given to external candidates from under-represented Member States*. The working languages of the Agency are English and French. A good knowledge of one of these is required. Knowledge of another Member State language would be an asset. *Member States, Associate Members or Cooperating States.', '2025-02-01 00:00:00+00', '2025-02-28 00:00:00+00', '2025-02-28 10:15:59.552964+00', '2025-03-17 06:05:15.359465+00', '2025-02-28 10:15:59.552964+00', 'draft', 'https://jobs.esa.int/job/Paris-ESA-Graduate-Trainee-in-Evaluation-and-Data-Analytics/1166158101/', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
	('2a0a2692-ea44-4dbc-bba3-667cd4b0bc37', '7ce7027f-397f-485a-82f1-537ac8b5c8f2', 'ESA Graduate Trainee in Support to Performance and Engineering Requirement Management', 'f2601046-ce81-48ef-8e14-db89efcd7aa6', 'Noordwijk, NL', 'Location ESTEC, Noordwijk, Netherlands Our team and mission The Laser Interferometer Space Antenna (LISA) is an ESA-led mission in partnership with NASA. LISA is the first space mission designed to observe the universe via gravitational waves, ripples in the fabric of space time caused by the acceleration of massive objects in the universe. Since January 2024 LISA is preparing to enter the Implementation Phase. The mission aims to determine how and when massive black holes in galactic nuclei formed and evolved over time. It will cover the mass-redshift parameter space to reconstruct their history. By examining gravitational wave signals from merging black holes, the mission will reveal their spin and redshifted mass to distinguish various formation scenarios. Additionally, it will analyse signals from thousands of stellar-mass binaries in the Galaxy, providing distances, orbital and mass parameters for compact binaries. This data will help map stars evolution and study tidal and non-gravitational influences on orbits due to the compact remnants'' internal physics. The LISA observatory consists of 3 spacecrafts forming an equilateral triangular constellation of 2.5 million km side-length, in trailing orbit with respect to the Earth at about 50 million km. The passage of a gravitational wave results in a modulation of the length of one arm with respect to another, which is detected using laser interferometry. LISA is planned to be launched on an Ariane 64 into a direct escape trajectory. Each spacecraft is endowed with electric propulsion for the transfer to its operational orbit, attained after 1.5 years, where, after the acquisition of the interferometric links between the three spacecraft, the gravitational wave observatory will operate for 4.5 years (nominally). ESA is responsible for the mission, including procurement of the three spacecraft and the launch vehicle together with the development of the ground segment to control and operate the spacecraft (from Mission Operation Centre â€“ MOC) and to perform the science mission planning and process the data products, including archiving (from the Science Operation Centre â€“ SOC). The ESA Member States and NASA contribute to the LISA mission with several payload elements, while ESA has the responsibility of the payload system aspects, including the integration and verification of all the payload elements onto the spacecraft. In LISA, ESA has also the overall responsibility of the verification of the mission performance at spacecraft and constellation level, under the control of the Mission and Performance team as part of the ESA LISA project. You will be a member of the ESA Project Team in the Performance Section but are expected to exchange also with all members of the team. To support the control of the performance allocations and the related requirements, a complex break down of performance allocations has been performed and is controlled by the Performance Team. A new requirements management software tool (JAMA) was installed recently by the Project Team and is being populated. You are encouraged to visit the ESA website: http://www.esa.int and https://www.esa.int/Science_Exploration/Space_Science/LISA Field(s) of activity/research for the traineeship Your main tasks and activities will include: interact and support the performance team with the management of the performance budget allocations and the associated mission requirements at all levels (entire mission, system, sub-system, unit); interact with JAMA and develop specific tools to support the visualisation of budget allocations and their logical relations at all levels in close interaction with our team; develop status overview tools (project dashboard) and implement process flows for the change and approval process, versioning and export for documentation in support of reviews; support the team with the import of requirements and their technical consolidation within the tool, such as verification of the import, separation of common data in a common field, cross-referencing of requirements and budget entries, etc. Additionally, you will support the development of interfaces from JAMA to performance modelling and simulation tools. Technical competencies Knowledge of relevant technical/functional domainsRelevant experience gained during internships, project work and/or extracurricular or other activitiesGeneral knowledge of the space sector and relevant activitiesKnowledge of ESA and its programmes/projectsBehavioural competencies Result Orientation Operational Efficiency Fostering Cooperation Relationship Management Continuous Improvement Forward Thinking For more information, please refer to ESA Core Behavioural Competencies guidebook Education You should have just completed, or be in the final year of your masterâ€™ s degree in engineering or computer sciences. Additional requirements You should have good interpersonal and communication skills and should be able to work in a multicultural environment, both independently and as part of a team. Previous experience of working in international teams can be considered an asset. Your motivation, overall professional perspective and career goals will also be explored during the later stages of the selection process. Diversity, Equity and Inclusiveness ESA is an equal opportunity employer, committed to achieving diversity within the workforce and creating an inclusive working environment. We therefore welcome applications from all qualified candidates irrespective of gender, sexual orientation, ethnicity, beliefs, age, disability or other characteristics. Applications from women are encouraged. At the Agency we value diversity, and we welcome people with disabilities. Whenever possible, we seek to accommodat